political\\july-20.json:
{
  "id": "july-20",
  "title": "The July 20 Plot, 1944",
  "subtitle": "Operation Valkyrie — the assassination attempt on Adolf Hitler",
  "category": "political",
  "date_published": "2024-03-01",
  "author": "VeteransLedger Archive",
  "image": "/storage/images/articles/july-20.jpg",
  "tags": [
    "resistance",
    "July 20",
    "Stauffenberg",
    "Valkyrie",
    "assassination"
  ],
  "summary": "On 20 July 1944, Colonel Claus von Stauffenberg placed a bomb beneath the conference table at Hitler's Wolf's Lair headquarters. Hitler survived; the conspirators were arrested and executed.",
  "body": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Operation Valkyrie was the most serious attempt on Hitler's life and the centrepiece of a planned military coup to overthrow the Nazi government. It was organised by a network of Wehrmacht officers, diplomats, and civilians who had concluded that Germany's only hope lay in removing Hitler and negotiating a separate peace with the Western Allies."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "The Conspirators"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The plot centred on Claus Schenk Graf von Stauffenberg, Chief of Staff of the Reserve Army, who combined access to Hitler with the physical capability to carry a bomb after losing an eye, a hand, and two fingers in Tunisia. Other key conspirators included Ludwig Beck (former Army Chief of Staff), Henning von Tresckow, Friedrich Olbricht, and civilian politicians including Carl Friedrich Goerdeler and Ulrich von Hassel."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "20 July 1944"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Stauffenberg flew to the Wolf's Lair in East Prussia carrying a briefcase bomb. He placed it beneath the oak conference table and excused himself. The bomb detonated at 12:42 PM, killing four officers. Hitler survived because the briefcase had been moved to the far side of the heavy oak table support, deflecting the blast."
    },
    {
